olo 1094","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Anglie","Broadbridge Manor, Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, Anglie"},"da":{"1068–":"1068–Afdød","1068–Male":"1068–Afdød","1074–Female":"1074–Afdød","1098–Male":"1098–Afdød","1126–Male":"1126–Afdød","1039–Male":"1039–Afdød","1046–Female":"1046–Afdød","1039":"1039","1126":"1126","1068":"1068","Abt 1067":"omkring 1067","1046":"1046","1098":"1098","about 1126":"omkring 1126","1074":"1074","Abt 1094":"omkring 1094","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Broadbridge Manor, Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, England"},"nl":{"1068–":"1068–Overleden","1068–Male":"1068–Overleden","1074–Female":"1074–Overleden","1098–Male":"1098–Overleden","1126–Male":"1126–Overleden","1039–Male":"1039–Overleden","1046–Female":"1046–Overleden","1039":"1039","1126":"1126","1068":"1068","Abt 1067":"circa 1067","1046":"1046","1098":"1098","about 1126":"circa 1126","1074":"1074","Abt 1094":"circa 1094","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Broadbridge Manor, Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, England"},"en":{"1068–":"1068–Deceased","1068–Male":"1068–Deceased","1074–Female":"1074–Deceased","1098–Male":"1098–Deceased","1126–Male":"1126–Deceased","1039–Male":"1039–Deceased","1046–Female":"1046–Deceased","1039":"1039","1126":"1126","1068":"1068","Abt 1067":"about 1067","1046":"1046","1098":"1098","about 1126":"about 1126","1074":"1074","Abt 1094":"about 1094","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Broadbridge Manor, Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Covert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey, of Norman origin): habitational name from the Norman hamlet of Couvert in Calvados or from some other locality similarly named from Old French <i>(le) covert</i> ‘the secret corner, refuge, or thicket’. Sussex surname forms with the definite article and no preposition are not nicknames from Old French <i>covert</i> ‘secret(ive)’, as has been suggested, but are either references to ‘Le Covert’ as the place of origin or represent the common Norman practice of substituting <i>le</i> for <i>de</i> in surnames. This surname is now extinct in Britain.","Americanized form of an unidentified Dutch or German name, perhaps   Kofoed   or German   Gobert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coovert","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>Couvert</b> or its Dutch form <b>Coevert</b>, see   Covert  ."]},{"name":"Kofoed","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Anders, Nanna.","Danish: from <i>ko</i> ‘cow’ + <i>fod</i> ‘foot’, hence a nickname for someone with a club foot or other deformity of the foot. Compare   Kofford  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Covert I was born in 1068, his father, Bartholomew Covert, was 29 and his mother, Mrs. Bartholomew Covert, was 22. He married Mrs. Richard Covert about 1094. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1068–":"1068–Surnud","1068–Male":"1068–Surnud","1074–Female":"1074–Surnud","1098–Male":"1098–Surnud","1126–Male":"1126–Surnud","1039–Male":"1039–Surnud","1046–Female":"1046–Surnud","1039":"1039","1126":"1126","1068":"1068","Abt 1067":"umbes 1067","1046":"1046","1098":"1098","about 1126":"umbes 1126","1074":"1074","Abt 1094":"umbes 1094","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Broadbridge Manor, Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1068–":"1068–Kuollut","1068–Male":"1068–Kuollut","1074–Female":"1074–Kuollut","1098–Male":"1098–Kuollut","1126–Male":"1126–Kuollut","1039–Male":"1039–Kuollut","1046–Female":"1046–Kuollut","1039":"1039","1126":"1126","1068":"1068","Abt 1067":"noin 1067","1046":"1046","1098":"1098","about 1126":"noin 1126","1074":"1074","Abt 1094":"noin 1094","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Broadbridge Manor, Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, England"},"fr":{"1068–":"1068–Décédé","1068–Male":"1068–Décédé","1074–Female":"1074–Décédée","1098–Male":"1098–Décédé","1126–Male":"1126–Décédé","1039–Male":"1039–Décédé","1046–Female":"1046–Décédée","1039":"1039","1126":"1126","1068":"1068","Abt 1067":"environ 1067","1046":"1046","1098":"1098","about 1126":"environ 1126","1074":"1074","Abt 1094":"environ 1094","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angleterre","Broadbridge Manor, Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Covert I est né en 1068, son père, Bartholomew Covert, avait 29 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Bartholome